05417nam a2200781Ia 9781503635937DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036359377 a10.1515/97815036359372doi  a(DE-B1597)665118  a(OCoLC)1408682474  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD2057.5.Z8bW54 2023 7aHIS0550002bisacsh04a338.1/85691223/eng/202303271 aWilliams, Elizabeth R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStates of Cultivation :bImperial Transition and Scientific Agriculture in the Eastern Mediterranean /cElizabeth R. Williams. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (446 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Ottoman World Series: Critical Studies in Empire, Nature, and Knowledge00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tNote on Transliteration -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- t1 Provincial Legibility and Ecologies of Extraction -- t2 “Agriculture from a Book” -- t3 The Trials and Tribulations of Tractors -- t4 The Politics of Agricultural Expertise and Education -- t5 Of Mice, Sunn Bugs, Drought, and Taxation -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe final decades of the Ottoman Empire and the period of the French mandate in Syria and Lebanon coincided with a critical period of transformation in agricultural technologies and administration. Chemical fertilizers and mechanized equipment inspired model farms while government officials and technocratic elites pursued new land tenure, credit-lending, and tax collection policies to maximize revenue. These policies transformed rural communities and environments and were central to projects of reform and colonial control—as well as to resistance of that control. States of Cultivation examines the processes and effects of agrarian transformation over more than a century as Ottoman, Syrian, Lebanese, and French officials grappled with these new technologies, albeit with different end goals. Elizabeth Williams investigates the increasingly fragmented natures produced by these contrasting priorities and the results of their intersection with regional environmental limits. Not only did post–World War I policies realign the economic space of the mandate states, but they shaped an agricultural legacy that continued to impact Syria and Lebanon post-independence. With this book, Williams offers the first comprehensive account of the shared technocratic ideals that animated these policies and the divergent imperial goals that not only reshaped the region's agrarian institutions, but produced representations of the region with repercussions well beyond the mandate's end.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAgricultural innovationszLebanonxHistoryy20th century. 0aAgricultural innovationszSyriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aAgriculture and statezLebanonxHistoryy20th century. 0aAgriculture and statezSyriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialism and sciencezLebanonxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialism and sciencezSyriaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aFrench mandate.  aLebanon.  aOttoman Empire.  aSyria.  aagriculture.  aenvironment.  aexpertise.  anetworks.  arural.  ascience.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr